# Verification Plan: __PROJECT_NAME__

> Updated on: __DATE__
>
> Define how correctness will be proven before large-scale implementation starts.

## 1. Test Goals

- Prevent command parsing failures, config ambiguity, and unstable exit codes early
- Prioritize the core command paths used by both terminal users and automation scripts

## 2. Test Layers

| Layer | Goal | Coverage | Tool / Method |
|---|---|---|---|
| White-box Unit | Verify command parsing and pure logic | flag rules, config merging, output formatting, key branches | [TBD, for example a unit test framework] |
| Integration | Verify command and dependency collaboration | file systems, remote APIs, external command execution | [TBD, for example command integration tests] |
| E2E | Verify real CLI execution | shell invocation, stdout, stderr, exit codes | [TBD, for example CLI end-to-end tests] |
| Performance | Verify performance targets | startup cost, batch runs, long output | [TBD, for example performance benchmarks] |
| Security | Verify security boundaries | argument injection, credential handling, sensitive output | [TBD, for example negative security tests] |

## 3. Requirement-to-Test Mapping

| Test ID | Requirement | Test Type | Core Assertion |
|---|---|---|---|
| `TEST-001` | `FR-001` | E2E | Users can complete the core flow when following the documented command usage |
| `TEST-002` | `FR-002` | Integration | Invalid flags, missing config, or dependency failures emit actionable output and a non-zero exit code |

Requirements:

- Every high-priority `FR-*` maps to at least one automated test
- White-box, performance, and security tests relevant to the current version must be included in the plan
- If a requirement cannot yet be verified automatically, document why and what the fallback verification is

## 4. First Red Tests

1. The core command does not trigger the intended flow
2. Invalid flags do not produce a clear failure message
3. A dependency failure still exits successfully or produces output that scripts cannot parse

## 5. Test Data and Fixtures

- Prepare valid, missing, and conflicting flag combinations
- Prepare stable fixtures and isolated directories for file systems, env vars, and remote integrations

## 5.1 White-Box Focus

- Argument parsing branches
- Config precedence conflicts
- Exit-code mapping logic

## 5.2 Performance Test Plan

- Key performance indicators: startup time and batch execution time
- Load scenarios: large inputs, repeated execution, long output
- Pass criteria: [for example common commands begin output within X seconds]

## 5.3 Security Test Plan

- Argument injection risk
- Environment-variable and credential exposure risk
- Whether error output leaks sensitive context

## 6. Regression Strategy

- All exposed commands, subcommands, and key flags must keep regression coverage
- Any change to exit codes, output format, or config precedence must add regression tests
- For destructive commands, keep dry-run or confirmation logic under test

## 7. Execution Guidance

- Start with the failing test for the first must-run command
- Prioritize output and exit-code paths that are most likely to be consumed by shell scripts
- If the test framework is not selected yet, write the test idea and assertions first, then choose tools later
- Do not implement first and come back to tests later; tests should constrain command boundaries and failure behavior

## 8. Definition of Completion

- Every high-priority requirement has at least one automated verification path
- Critical failure scenarios are covered
- Bug fixes include regression tests
- Test commands can be run repeatedly with stable results
- White-box, performance, and security requirements are either satisfied or explicitly deferred with justification
